    <title>Permissions & Licensing - StoryLoom</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/style.css">
</head>
<body>

    {{> header}}

    <main class="container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h1>Permissions, Licensing and other Common Requests</h1>

            <h2>Overview</h2>
            <p>StoryLoom receives many requests for permissions to use texts or excerpts. Most such requests do not need a custom response, since permission is included in the items themselves (even for commercial use), or in the narrative below.</p>
            
            <div class="toc-box">
                <h3>Contents</h3>
                <ul class="dashed-list">
                    <li><a href="#not-needed">Most permissions not needed</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#terms">Terms of Use</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#trademark">Trademark Permission</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#linking">Linking</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#crediting">Crediting</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#quotes">Quotes and extracts</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#copyright">Copyright page and trademarks from Source</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#citing">Citing StoryLoom</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#paperwork">No paperwork</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#us-only">US only</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#sweat">No "sweat of the brow"</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#commercial">Commercial use</a></li>
                    <li><a href="#reporting">Reporting errata</a></li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h2 id="not-needed">Most permissions not needed</h2>
            <p>Most requests we receive do not require a response. The vast majority of StoryLoom texts are in the public domain in the US. This means that anyone can use them for virtually any purpose, without asking permission.</p>

            <h2 id="terms">Terms of Use</h2>
            <p>Accessing the website and utilizing its assets implies an acceptance of our general <a href="/terms">Terms of Use</a>.</p>

            <h2 id="trademark">Trademark Permission to "Trade On" the StoryLoom name</h2>
            <p>The name StoryLoom is intended as a brand identity. If you are simply utilizing the public domain texts, you do not need permission. However, if you intend to sell a product and brand it with the StoryLoom name, royalties or specific licensing agreements may apply.</p>

            <h2 id="linking">Linking</h2>
            <p>No permission is needed to link to the StoryLoom property, any page or address within it. To link to a specific text, link to the landing page for that text, not to the specific file. For example, link to the HTML landing page rather than deep-linking to the specific `.txt` file, which may change.</p>

            <h2 id="crediting">Crediting</h2>
            <p>No permission is needed to credit StoryLoom as the source of an item being used. This applies even for commercial uses.</p>

            <h2 id="quotes">Quotes and extracts from StoryLoom items</h2>
            <p>No permission is needed to use quotes from StoryLoom items in the US. They are in the public domain. This applies for all use, including commercial use.</p>

            <h2 id="copyright">Copyright page and trademarks from Source</h2>
            <p>Sometimes a text will include a transcription or image of the original title page, including publisher names or publication dates. This might include extinct publisher names or marks. StoryLoom is providing such items "as is," with no representation of ownership of whether any such marks are still active.</p>

            <h2 id="citing">Citing StoryLoom</h2>
            <p>You can use any standard bibliographic format to cite the free texts you find in StoryLoom. We use "StoryLoom" as the publication source, since that is the digital home of our efforts.</p>

            <h2 id="paperwork">No paperwork</h2>
            <p>StoryLoom will not sign paperwork or legal releases asserting our ownership of texts. The texts are largely in the public domain, meaning we do not own them either, and thus cannot grant explicit written permission for you to use them.</p>

            <h2 id="us-only">US only</h2>
            <p>StoryLoom's primary clearance framework follows United States laws for copyright. Items that are in the public domain in the US are generally in the public domain in other countries, and vice versa, but if you are operating outside of the US, you should get professional guidance on how to proceed.</p>

            <h2 id="sweat">No "sweat of the brow"</h2>
            <p>StoryLoom claims no copyright or markup formatting on the texts. The act of digitizing and proofreading does not create a new copyright under US Law.</p>

            <h2 id="commercial">Commercial use</h2>
            <p>Because the texts are in the public domain, you are generally free to utilize the raw `.txt` files for commercial purposes without restriction or royalty, provided you do not use our trademarked branding to sell them.</p>

            <h2 id="reporting">Reporting errata</h2>
            <p>If you find an error, please report it to our contact email. Please note that because of the volume of texts, bug fixes and textual corrections are handled entirely by volunteers and may take time to reflect on the main site.</p>

        </div>
    </main>

    {{> footer}}

</body>
</html>